The most common home internet connection type in Australia is a fixed-line NBN connection, but more people are turning to home wireless plans as a viable alternative, so we'll eventually look at those, too.

That said, 'cheapest' doesn't necessarily mean it will also suit your needs. You might need to scroll a little further to see our comparisons of different internet types and speeds.

Cheap internet plans on the NBN

When it comes to the NBN, cheaper plans are often slower speed tiers, but the gap between NBN 100 and slower plans is shrinking thanks to continued changes in NBN Co's wholesale pricing. That said, you don't necessarily need to go it slow to get a cheap internet plan – sometimes you can keep your internet speed and save money just by switching providers.

It's also important to consider that many NBN plans are discounted for the first six months, after which they go up in price – sometimes considerably. Because lock-in contracts are largely a thing of the past (unless you're paying off hardware, such as a WiFi modem), you can usually switch internet providers pretty easily.

Changing providers regularly can save you a considerable percentage of your monthly fees because of these intro deals, as long as you remember to switch to another cheap internet plan before your discount period runs out. If this doesn't sound like your cup of tea, don't worry. We'll also compare plans based on the total cost over the first 12 months to help even things out.

If you're thinking about saving money by dropping your data limit, you might find that difficult. Most providers focus on unlimited plans these days. You can sometimes still find cheaper internet plans that aren't unlimited, but they're rare and tend to have restrictive data caps.

NBN 25: cheapest internet plans

If you want a cheap internet plan and don't have high usage demands, NBN 25 can be a good choice. 

With maximum download speeds of 25 megabits per second (Mbps), NBN 25 can be enough to accommodate two people with moderate internet usage. Not only that, NBN 25 is usually cheaper than NBN 12, meaning you get better speed for a cheaper price.

NBN 50: cheapest internet plans

While NBN 50 plans used to be a good balance of speed and affordability, that's not necessarily the case anymore. Thanks to changes in how NBN Co prices its wholesale plans, many providers have been increasing the cost of NBN 50 faster than for NBN 100. As such, you can pay a similar amount for an internet plan with 50Mbps downloads and one with 100Mbps.

When looking at initial discount periods, these two speed tiers can actually cost the same per month from the same provider. It's usually the post-discount prices where you'll find NBN 50 offers cheaper internet plans – but even then, possibly not by much.

NBN 100: cheapest internet plans

When thinking of a cheap internet plan, NBN 100, might not be the first thing that springs to mind. But while NBN 50 and NBN 25 plans increase in cost, NBN 100 plans from many providers have either stayed the same or seen smaller price hikes. So, in terms of speed versus price, NBN 100 can represent a better bargain (assuming you'll make use of those faster internet speeds).

As part of their first-six-month discount period, many providers charge the same or a similar rate for their NBN 100 plans as they do for NBN 50. The price difference only kicks in once you pass the six month marker. Even then, the long-term difference is often still small.

As such, you can get a great deal if you swap providers every six months. It might sound like a pain, but switching providers usually doesn't take very long, and the savings can make it well worth your time.

What about NBN 12?

Even if you're looking for the cheapest internet plan possible, NBN 12 plans are unlikely to be a good  option because they often cost more than NBN 25, which itself is getting more expensive at a decent clip. Essentially, you get a slower connection and can pay more for the privilege.

While you might think you can get by on 12Mbps, the real kicker is the harsh 1Mbps upload limit. Uploads aren't just important because they let you backup or send files – if you max out your upload bandwidth, it also tanks your download speed because all internet traffic is two way, if only to a small degree.

By comparison, an NBN 25 plan has a maximum upload speed of 5Mbps. This still isn't a lot, but it's a significant step up from 1Mbps.

Cheap internet plans for home wireless

If your NBN connection isn't up to snuff, you might consider a home wireless plan. These connections run via 4G and 5G mobile broadband networks, but use a modem router similar to the one you'll have for the NBN.

5G home internet in particular can be faster than fixed-line NBN plans of the same price, whereas the slower 4G plans are more focused on cost-saving, rather than bang for buck. So, if you're looking for the absolute cheapest internet plan, 4G might be your option. But this is mostly the case for anyone interested in NBN 12 or possibly NBN 25 speeds.

If you're looking for a cheap alternative to NBN 50 and above, 5G home internet is likely what you'll need.

5G home wireless: cheapest internet plans

The 5G network footprint is still growing, but it's large enough to cover many or most metro areas (though not necessarily from all telcos). It's also surprisingly affordable, often cheaper than comparable NBN plans.

Cheap 5G home internet plans start with speeds of 50Mbps, but you can get faster 100Mbps plans, as well as uncapped options that can achieve over 200Mbps. These are comparable to NBN 50, NBN 100, and NBN 250, respectively.

How do I choose between cheap internet plans?

When choosing a cheap internet plan, you'll want to cover the basics first:

  • Price: Remember, the cheapest internet plan isn't always the best for your needs. Ask yourself two questions: 'what do I need this internet connection to do for me?', and 'how much am I willing to pay for it?' Also be sure to pay attention to both the initial pricing and the pricing after six months – the difference can be significant.

  • Data allowance: For the most part, even the cheapest internet plans for home use have unlimited data. Almost every NBN or home wireless plan is unlimited, so this likely isn't something you have to consider. If you come across a plan with a fixed data allowance, make sure it meets your needs (e.g. Telstra's 1TB allowances will likely be just fine). For more info, check out our detailed guide to internet data usage.

  • Download speeds: Slower internet plans are cheaper, but they're also limiting. Ensure you're getting an NBN speed tier that will be enough for your household. NBN 50 is still the most commonly used speed tier in Australia. This is equivalent to a 5G home wireless plan with a 50Mbps speed cap, as long as you have sufficient 5G coverage. But you might need 100Mbps if your internet demands are higher. Most households don't need NBN 250 just yet, but give it a few years and that might change.

  • Extras and perks: Extras can inch an ISP a little higher up in your good books. For example, does your prospective internet plan come with a free modem and delivery, or is that a cost you have to pay (assuming you don't already have one)? Likewise, is the deal being sweetened with some sort of streaming entertainment package that comes with a free set-top box and subscription to a service, or are you getting said box but no (or a limited time) subscription that equals more cost in the long run? Be sure to check the fine print.

Cheap internet plans FAQs

What is the cheapest internet plan for basic use?

NBN 12 (aka 'Basic I') is the most basic plan type in most of Australia, but aren't always the cheapest internet plans around. In many cases, faster NBN 25 plans can be cheaper than NBN 12. Also keep in mind that NBN 12 might not come close to meeting your bandwidth needs, particularly with regards to uploads. 4G home wireless can offer even cheaper internet plans, but they're usually slower than NBN 25.

Can I get internet for free?

In general, free internet is hard to come by outside of free public WiFi.  Some programs help disadvantaged people get online at reduced rates, but these are very few. One such program is the government's School Student Broadband Initiative (SSBI). The SSBI aims to provide free internet to 30,000 families with school-aged children facing financial hardship. 

How can I get a cheap internet plan?

Shopping around frequently and comparing similar options is the easiest way to get a cheap internet plan. Make sure you're getting the most value for money with your plan and also getting the right service.

Switching providers is usually fast and easy, so it's not much of a hassle to sign up to another cheap internet plan once you've found it. The same goes for switching providers regularly to make sure you keep getting those first-six-months discounted rates.
